, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"fontface" : 3,
					"fontsize" : 11.0,
					"id" : "obj-6",
					"linecount" : 17,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 74.925659266864272, 260.129280764682562, 850.0, 224.0 ],
					"text" : "I developed the idea of Chréode’s functions while researching basic universal principles to organize musical composition. \nI was at that time (1981) working on the Chant program at Ircam, in which the synthesis technique invented by Xavier Rodet, \nformant wave synthesis, is actually based on damped sinusoids. The capacity to generate with Chant an infinite range of sounds \nfrom simple transformations of a sinusoid fascinated me, and I decided to try to apply the same idea to musical structures.\nBetween other musical endeavours, my aim was to use the form of the damped sinusoid to construct processes with strong \ndirectionalities, and to achieve interactions between structure and sound material through their common basic principles. \n\nThis research ended rather quickly since I was soon after taken by responsibilities in Ircam that did not let me time. \nHowever, the original code was perpetuated through all the generations of aid to composition systems: \nfirst written by Pierre Conte with the program Formes (meant to control Chant), it was later ported to Esquisse, \nthe first CAC environment developed at Ircam (in the Musical Research department I was directing), by Jacques Duthen \n& Pierre-François Baisnée. It was later ported to OM and PWGL by Kilian Sprotte. \n\nI am particularly happy that Julien Vincenot finally ported it to Bach and MOZ'Lib: it gives unprecedented possibilities \nto visualize and manipulate musically the data, and therefore to interact more critically with such generative processes. \nIt is a very good set of tools pedagogically, to apprehend the potential and limits of musical processes. \nCongratulations and thanks to Julien!",
					"textcolor" : [ 0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0 ]
				}

