					"text" : "As a matter of fact, the original code on 'Le Lisp' was almost undecipherable because of its very \nspecific syntax: Chréode is mainly based on object-oriented programming, and its programming interface \nhad very few in common with the standardized CLOS (Common Lisp Object System) that we know today.\n\nThe modular nature of the original library gave way naturally to its current form in MOZ'Lib : \nsimilarly to the original MOZ modules themselves, Chréode now consists of a collection of bpatchers. \nThe majority of them aims to generate a piece of Lisp code dynamically. The user needs to connect \nthose boxes together, according to the rules of the Chréode system, in order to produce morphologies \nwhich can control a variety of musical parameters.",
